Writing a Michaelis-Menten Function

Fixed Values: Umax = 1 Ks = 100 Formula U = Umax S / Ks + S

mm_function <- function(Um, Ks, S){
 U <- Um*S/(Ks+S)
 plot(S,U)
 }
S <- seq(from = 0, to = 200, by = 1)
mm_function(Um =1, Ks = 100, S = S)

If Else Function

Format: ifelse(test, yes, no) test is an object that can be coerced into a logical true/false for each element in the vector Yes returns values for true elements in the test no returns values for fasle elements in the test

Examples: suppose we have an insect pop in which each female lays on average 10.2 eggs, following a Poisson distribution. lambda = 10.2 here. However, there is a 35% chance of parasatism, in which case no eggs are laid. Here is a random sample of eggs laid for a group of 1000 individuals.

#makes 1000 random uniform values 
tester <- runif(1000)
eggs <- ifelse(tester > 0.35, rpois(n=1000, lambda=10.2), 0)
hist(eggs)

This produces a mixture model where there is a peak at ~10.2. Also a spike at zero, which represents the 0s created from Poisson itself, but also the 35% of individuals that didnt reproduce due to parasitism.

Example 2: Suppose we have a vector of probability values (such as from a simulation). We want to highlight significant values in the vector for plotting

p_vals <- runif(1000)
z <- ifelse(p_vals <=0.025, "lower_tail", "non_significant")
z[p_vals >=0.975] <- "upper_tail"

table(z)
## z
##      lower_tail non_significant      upper_tail 
##              27             942              31

Dyanmic Models - Exponential growth model

Formula: Nt = N0 e^kt Known values: K = 0.05 N0 =10

#as a function
dyn_function <- function(K,N0){ 
 Nt <- N0*exp(K*t)
 plot(t,Nt)
}
t <- seq(from = 0, to = 200, by = 0.5)
dyn_function(K=0.05, N0= 10)

#not as a function, as a single vector.

### Ricker Model Formula: Nt+1 = Nt*e(rmax(1-N/K)) Known values: k = 100 r = 1.5 t = 0 to 100 Were forced to write a loop, because the current value is the input for the following value. Need a starting value, so well use: N1= 60

#t <- seq(0:100)
k <- 100
r <- 3.0
N <- NA
N[1] <- 60
t <- seq(1:100)

#the below works, but I also want to standardize the way I assigned the length so it's not fixed in the loop but rather pre-assigned. 

# for(i in 2:100) {
#   N[i] <- N[i-1]*exp(r*(1-N[i-1]/k))
# }

for(i in 2:length(t-1)) {
  N[i] <- N[i-1]*exp(r*(1-N[i-1]/k))
}
#plotting N over time 
plot(t, N, type = "l", ylim = c(0,300))

#plotting Nt vs Nt-1 as a plot. This is following a pattern and deterministic, even though prior graph looks like pure chaos. 
# Phase-space diagram 
plot(N[1:99], N[2:100])

### Numerical Approximation Formulas were using: Exponential growth Nt = N0e^kt Numerical approximation: Nt = Nt-1 KNt-1 deltaT Known values: K = 0.01 N0 =1 up to t =20 Goal: plot both on same axis, use different colors.

K <- 0.1 

NNt <- NA
NNt[1] <- 1
N0 <- 1
t <- seq(from =1, to = 20, by = 1)
#exponential 
ENt <- N0*exp(K*t)
#numerical integration 
for(i in 2:length(t-1)) {
  NNt[i] <- NNt[i-1]+K*NNt[i-1]*1 
}

#N[i] <- N[i-1]*exp(r*(1-N[i-1]/k))
plot(t, ENt, type= "line", col = "violet",ylab = "Nt")
## Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): plot type 'line' will be truncated to first
## character
lines(t, NNt, col= "cornflowerblue")

### Numerical Integration of Lotka- Volterra Model Formulas: Nt = Nt-1 + (rNt-1 - aNt-1Pt-1) delta t Pt = Pt-1+ (abNt-1 Pt-1 - sPt-1) delta t Known values : delta t = 0.1 length of run = 2000 n[1] = 20 p[1] = 1 r = 0.04 a = 0.005 s= 0.1

n <- seq(from = 1, to = 200.9, by =0.1)
Nt <- NA
Nt[1] <- 20
Pt <- NA
Pt[1] <- 1
r <- 0.04
a <- 0.005 
b <- 0.2
s <- 0.1
deltat <- 0.1

for (i in 2:length(n)) { 
  Nt[i] <- Nt[i-1] + (r*Nt[i-1] - a*Nt[i-1]*Pt[i-1])*(n[i]-n[i-1])
  Pt[i] <- Pt[i-1] + (a*b*Nt[i-1]*Pt[i-1]- s*Pt[i-1])*(n[i]-n[i-1])
}

plot(n, Nt, col = "violet",ylab = "Nt")
lines(n, Pt, col= "darkblue")

#phase diagram is a circle 
#there is an equilibrium that exists in the center of this circle. As N goes up, then P catches, and raises until N decreases and P does again. 
plot(Nt, Pt)
